  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Mackenzie sits on the southern edge of Carindale in Brisbane's southeastern corridor, tucked between Mansfield to the south, Wishart to the southwest and the Belmont Hills Reserve to the east. The suburb is small in footprint, lightly populated relative to its neighbours, and almost entirely residential, with the larger Brisbane City Council yards and depots forming the western boundary. The combination of bushland-edge character, low through-traffic streets, and proximity to Westfield Carindale gives Mackenzie a setting that buyers describe as quiet without being remote.</p>

      <p>Mackenzie's market is defined by its scarcity. Annual turnover is genuinely low because the suburb has fewer total properties than Carindale or Mansfield and the resident profile is weighted toward long-term owner-occupiers who have stayed for the bushland setting and the access to Westfield, the Gateway Motorway, and the wider southeastern corridor. When a quality home does come to market, the buyer attention from across the corridor is concentrated, and that scarcity dynamic is one of the most important factors for a seller to understand when planning a Mackenzie campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Mackenzie</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer in Mackenzie is the family that has been comparing Carindale and Mansfield and has arrived at Mackenzie as the quieter alternative. These buyers want the lifestyle infrastructure that Carindale provides (the Westfield centre, the school options, the Gateway access) but want the residential streets to be calmer than the busier Carindale arterials. They have visited enough open homes across the corridor to know exactly what they want, and they arrive at Mackenzie ready to act when the right property appears.</p>

      <p>The second consistent buyer group is the downsizer from a larger Carindale or Belmont block who wants to stay close to the area but reduce maintenance commitment. These buyers are familiar with the southeastern corridor, have established networks they want to retain, and are looking for a quality home on a manageable block in a known and trusted setting. Mackenzie's bushland edge and quiet streets are part of the appeal for this segment.</p>

      <p>The third buyer pool is the upgrader from a more compact southern Brisbane address who is making the move out to a larger block in the corridor. These buyers tend to be in their thirties or early forties, with growing families, and they have decided that the time has come to trade proximity to the inner city for the space and quiet that Mackenzie provides.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Mackenzie</h2>
      <p>The bushland edge is a meaningful value driver. Properties that border the Belmont Hills Reserve or sit on elevated streets with reserve outlook command attention from buyers who specifically want that setting. The premium these properties hold over otherwise comparable Mackenzie homes that sit deeper in the suburb away from the reserve is consistent and observable in comparable sales analysis.</p>

      <p>Block size and street position matter. Mackenzie has a discernible internal hierarchy of streets, with the quieter residential cul-de-sacs and through streets that lead to the reserve commanding stronger demand than streets that feed back into the busier Mansfield Road or Mt Petrie Road corridors. Buyers comparing the suburb have usually formed clear views on which streets they prefer before they reach the open home, and the property's street position is part of the value proposition that the campaign should reflect.</p>

      <p>Proximity to Westfield Carindale is a practical asset that buyers factor into their decision. Mackenzie's position means a five-minute drive to one of southeast Queensland's largest retail centres, the access to the Gateway Motorway for airport and Gold Coast journeys, and the connection to the wider southeastern arterial network. That practical infrastructure access supports value across the suburb.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Mackenzie home for sale</h2>
      <p>Mackenzie's small annual turnover means buyer attention is concentrated when a quality home appears, and the preparation standard sets the tone of the campaign. A property that presents well from day one, with practical condition items addressed, considered landscaping, and well-staged interior spaces, draws the active Carindale and Mansfield buyer pool into the conversation immediately and creates the competitive atmosphere that produces a strong result.</p>

      <p>The bushland setting is part of the value proposition for many Mackenzie properties, and presentation should make use of that. Outdoor entertaining areas with reserve outlook, well-maintained gardens that frame the bushland edge, and considered landscaping that responds to the natural setting all reinforce the buyer's reason for choosing Mackenzie over its more conventional neighbours.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Mackenzie</h2>
      <p>Mackenzie follows the broader Brisbane seasonal pattern, with autumn (late February through May) and spring (September through November) as the strongest windows. Autumn is particularly productive for the southeastern corridor because families who have been researching the area through summer arrive in February and March with clear intent and a defined timeline. Spring brings more buyers to the market but also more competing listings across the wider corridor, and the autumn window's lower competing stock profile often gives a well-prepared Mackenzie home a cleaner run.</p>

      <p>Because Mackenzie's annual turnover is low to begin with, the scarcity advantage of a well-timed campaign is amplified. A Mackenzie property that launches when there is genuinely no other directly comparable Mackenzie listing on the market is positioned to attract the full attention of the active corridor buyer pool, and that scarcity dynamic is one of the strongest factors in producing a result that exceeds the seller's expectations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Mackenzie</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Mackenzie homes, accurately priced against the most recent comparable sales for the specific street and property type, typically sell within 28 to 45 days. The buyer pool is smaller than for Carindale or Mansfield, but it is also more committed because Mackenzie is rarely a buyer's first option until they have specifically decided that the bushland-edge quiet suburban character is what they want. Once that decision is made, the buyer tends to act decisively when a correctly-priced property appears.</p>

      <p>Correct pricing against current comparables is the most controllable factor in campaign duration. Mackenzie's low turnover means comparable sales analysis requires a wider look across the immediate neighbouring suburbs of Carindale and Mansfield to triangulate the right number, and that analysis is part of the planning work that distinguishes a campaign that closes within the normal window from one that drifts beyond it.</p>

